Sandfly API Service SSL Certificate
===================================

The Sandfly server automatically manages TLS certificates. By default, it
generates a self-signed certificate that is stored in the database.

To use your own SSL/TLS certificate instead, place two files in this directory:

  - cert.pem       - Your server certificate (and chain)
  - privatekey.pem - Your private key

When both files are present, the server will use them instead of auto-generated
certificates. If either file is missing, the server uses automatic TLS.

After updating the certificate files, you can reload them without restarting
the server by running:

    ./setup_scripts/reload_server_https_certificate.sh


cert.pem
--------

The cert.pem file must contain the server certificate and (if necessary) the
intermediate chain certificate(s).

The server certificate must be the first certificate in the file. Each
certificate must be PEM-encoded with "-----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----" and
"-----END CERTIFICATE-----" delimiters.

If you have your server certificate in certificate.pem and your intermediate
certificates in cachain.pem, create cert.pem by concatenating them:

    cat certificate.pem cachain.pem > cert.pem

The complete file should look like:

    -----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----
    MII...
    -----END CERTIFICATE-----
    -----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----
    MII...
    -----END CERTIFICATE-----


privatekey.pem
--------------

The privatekey.pem file must be a PEM-encoded, unencrypted private key:

    -----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----
    MII...
    -----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----


Let's Encrypt / ACME
--------------------

The server has built-in support for automatically obtaining and renewing
certificates from Let's Encrypt. This can be configured through the server's
configuration settings. When ACME mode is enabled, the server handles all
certificate management automatically.
